	affiliations = {Tiangong University, School of Life Sciences, Tianjin, China; Tianjin Medical University Cancer Institute & Hospital, Tianjin, Tianjin, China; Tianjin Rehabilitation Convalescent Center, Tianjin, Tianjin, China},
	abstract = {In lung cancer radiation therapy, precise segmentation of Organ-at-Risk (OAR) is essential to reduce radiation exposure to healthy tissues. However, the low contrast of OAR in computed tomography (CT) and anatomical variability among patients present considerable challenges. To address these, this study proposed a novel segmentation framework MSC U-Net based on the U-Net architecture. A pyramid structure was formed by integrating multi-scale images into each encoder layer. And the CSLA(Channel Spatial Linear Attention) was introduced in skip connections. Additionally, a ResX structure was employed to refine channel features. Then MSC U-Net was validated with a dataset of 96 lung cancer patients, 76 cases for training and 20 for testing. Compared with the 9 kinds of enhanced U-Net variants, MSC U-Net obtained better performance for segmentation of critical organs. Finally, The segmentation results were evaluated by DSC, IoU, and ASD metrics. MSC U-Net achieved DSC of 92.78 % for heart, 96.46 % for right lung, 96.94 % for left lung, 77.71 % for spinal cord and 80.68 % for esophagus which surpassed the standard U-Net by 0.84 %, 0.77 %, 0.53 %, 0.65 % and 4.28 %, respectively. In conclusion, this proposed MSC U-Net architecture can acquire accurate and efficient segmentation for critical organs in chest CT which has clinical application potential in lung cancer radiation therapy. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
