	abstract = {With the rising prevalence of mental disorders globally, there is an urgent need for more and more patients to receive early diagnosis and treatment. However, the current diagnostic approach for brain disorders is primarily based on subjective symptom criteria derived from clinical observation, which is both time-consuming and costly. In this study, we developed a deep learning framework that combines Channel-Space Self-Attention-Mechanism and convolutional networks (CSAM-CNN) to discriminate diseased participants from healthy controls using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) and diffusion tensor imaging (DTI), which helps clinicians in the early detection and categorization of brain illnesses. Specifically, firstly multimodal neuroimaging data and clinical priors are fused to create a disease-specific brain network. Then, a self-attention mechanism is proposed for obtaining spatial and temporal representations in brain networks. In addition, non-imaging information (age, gender, etc.) is introduced to address the issue of brain biology being ignored in disease classification tasks. Extensive experiments on disease prediction tasks demonstrate that the proposed CSAM-CNN achieves 92% and 93.94% classification accuracy on ABIDE (Autism Brain Imaging Data Exchange) and COBRE (Centre for Biomedical Research Excellence) datasets, respectively. Furthermore, our model can identify brain regions associated with autism spectrum disorder (ASD) and schizophrenia (SZ). The approach accounts for individual differences and has the potential for application and clinical use in various brain diseases. © 2025 IEEE.},
