	abstract = {Purpose – This study aimed to uncover the themes and types of information shared among parents of children with autism spectrum disorder (ASD) in an online community and to elucidate the relationship between them. Design/methodology/approach – Utilizing Houyi Crawler software, this study initially gathered 8, 575 posts from the designated “Autism Bar” section within Baidu Tieba, a popular Chinese online community, after which 3, 673 relevant posts were retained. The posts underwent rigorous qualitative analysis using open coding to precisely identify the themes and subthemes related to information sharing among parents of children with ASD. Findings – First, the study identified 10 major themes and 37 subthemes that encapsulated the intricate nature of information sharing among Chinese parents of children with ASD in an online community. Second, these parents predominantly shared experiential information rich in cognitive–affective insights, although other types of information such as facts and descriptions were also shared to a lesser degree. Third, a specific correlation was identified between themes and types of information shared within this community. Originality/value – The study is among the first to characterize empirically the themes and types of information shared by parents of children with ASD through examining the articulations of online discussants. © 2025 Emerald Publishing Limited},
