	year = {2025},
	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1109/IACIS65746.2025.11211005},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105023639576&doi=10.1109%2FIACIS65746.2025.11211005&partnerID=40&md5=e93bcd2c420c8bed36271f41a7ffdc79},
	affiliations = {REVA University, School of Computer Science and Applications, Bengaluru, KA, India; REVA University, School of Electronics and Communication Engineering, Bengaluru, KA, India},
	abstract = {Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) is a complex neurodevelopmental condition characterized by deficits in social communication, restricted interests, and repetitive behaviors. Early and accurate diagnosis is critical for effective intervention, yet traditional diagnostic methods are often timeconsuming, subjective, and inaccessible in resource-limited settings. Recent advances in machine learning (ML) offer promising avenues for automating and enhancing ASD diagnosis by leveraging behavioral, neuroimaging, and genetic data. This paper explores the application of supervised and unsupervised ML algorithms - including Support Vector Machines (SVM), Random Forests (RF), and Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) - to identify ASD-related patterns across diverse datasets. Ensemble learning techniques have demonstrated superior performance in generalizability and accuracy, particularly when applied to pediatric and adult questionnaire responses. Neuroimaging modalities such as resting-state functional MRI (rs-fMRI) have further enabled the extraction of functional connectivity biomarkers, improving classification precision. Explainable AI (XAI) frameworks are increasingly integrated to enhance model transparency and clinical trust. Despite these advancements, challenges persist in data heterogeneity, model interpretability, and clinical integration. This study synthesizes current methodologies, evaluates their diagnostic efficacy, and proposes a hybrid ML framework optimized for early ASD detection. The findings underscore the potential of ML to democratize ASD screening, reduce diagnostic bottlenecks, and support scalable, community-based interventions. Future directions include multimodal data fusion, real-time detection systems, and ethical governance for AI deployment in clinical settings. © 2025 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {autism spectrum disorder (ASD); random forest; support vector machine (SVM)},
	keywords = {Computer aided diagnosis; Convolutional neural networks; Diseases; Ethical aspects; Functional neuroimaging; Learning systems; Real time systems; Autism spectrum disorder; Autism spectrum disorders; Behavioral data; Condition; Diagnostic methods; Machine-learning; Random forests; Social communications; Support vector machine; Support vectors machine; Support vector machines},
