	abstract = {Autism spectrum disorder (ASD) is a neuro developmental condition that affects social communication, behavior, and everyday functioning. Early intervention is promising in reducing the symptoms' severity, making an early and accurate diagnosis quite important. Identification of (ASD), which is necessary to facilitate early intervention and aid individuals affected. Many techniques have been introduced for the early detection of ASD using advanced techniques. This study investigates a dual methodology for autism detection that incorporates both structured data and image datasets. We utilize machine learning algorithms, specifically Random Forest (RF), AdaBoost (ADA), and Support Vector Machine (SVM), to categorize individuals as either autistic or non-autistic. Additionally, a convolutional neural network (CNN) was employed for the classification of images related to autism diagnoses. The performance metrics, including accuracy and precision of these models, were thoroughly analyzed and compared to evaluate their efficacy in detecting ASD. These metrics help to identify the bestperforming algorithms and optimal FS techniques for this type of dataset. For image data, a CNN model is implemented to improve prediction by capturing patterns associated with ASD in visual form. The work emphasizes the possibility of developing scalable and automated screening applications for ASD to be used for early diagnosis and intervention. © 2025 IEEE.},
