	affiliations = {Brigham Young University, Provo, UT, United States},
	abstract = {Virtual reality (VR) is an emerging tool in special education that enables immersive, individualized, and engaging learning experiences for students with autism spectrum disorder (ASD). This article explores the benefits, challenges, and practical implementation of VR in classroom settings to support social interaction, executive functioning, sensory regulation, and life skills. It outlines a comparison of commercially available VR headsets, sensory accommodations for students with ASD, and strategies for customizing VR content aligned with individualized education program (IEP) goals. Additionally, the paper highlights recommended applications, addresses safety and ethical considerations, and discusses accessibility features critical for inclusive VR integration. While VR offers exciting possibilities, challenges such as high costs, limited teacher training, and infrastructure demands remain. Potential solutions include collaborative partnerships, professional development, and scalable models that enhance long-term implementation. As VR continues to evolve, it holds promise as a transformative tool for promoting engagement, autonomy, and growth among students with disabilities. © The Author(s) 2025},
