	affiliations = {Pabna University of Science and Technology, Department of Computer Science and Engineering, Pabna, Rajshahi, Bangladesh},
	abstract = {Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) is a neurodevelopmental illness that frequently coexists with Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD), which makes early detection challenging. This study introduces a machine learning approach for identifying ADHD in children with ASD based on handwriting analysis. We collected a dataset of handwriting samples from 29 Japanese children (14 with ADHD with ASD and 15 healthy controls) as they completed zigzag and periodic line tasks on a pen tablet. More than thirty features were extracted, including geometric, kinematic, pressure-related, and angular aspects. The Extra Trees model performed the best among the fivefold cross-validation classifiers (accuracy: 92.59 %, recall: 1.0, precision: 84.61 %, AUC: 0.9203). Task-specific results included notable AUCs for Random Forest (PL-trace: 0.8791), Gradient Boosting (Zigzag-predict: 0.7472) and Logistic Regression (Zigzag-trace: 0.7692) highlighting the potential of these handwriting-based systems for ADHD-ASD detection. The findings emphasize handwriting analysis as an excellent, non-invasive tool for detecting ADHD in ASD populations. © 2025 IEEE.},
