	affiliations = {College of Sciences, Department of Statistics and Operations Research, Riyadh, Riyad, Saudi Arabia; Galala University, Faculty of Science, Suez, Suez, Egypt; Faculty of Computers and Information, Damietta, Damietta, Egypt; Faculty of Applied Technological Health Sciences, Technology of Radiology and Medical Imaging Program, Suez, Suez, Egypt; Zhejiang Normal University, School of Computer Science and Technology, Jinhua, Zhejiang, China; Taif University, Department of Mathematics and Statistics, Taif, Makkah al Mukarramah, Saudi Arabia; Faculty of Science, Zagazig, Sharqia, Egypt; Ajman University, College of Engineering and Information Technology, Ajman, Ajman, United Arab Emirates; Al-Ahliyya Amman University, Hourani Center for Applied Scientific Research, Amman, Jordan; Galala University, Faculty of Computer Science and Engineering, Suez, Suez, Egypt},
	abstract = {Introduction: Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) is a neurodevelopmental condition characterized by challenges in communication, social interactions, and repetitive behaviors. The heterogeneity of symptoms across individuals complicates diagnosis. Neuroimaging techniques, particularly resting-state functional MRI (rs-fMRI), have shown potential for identifying neural signatures of ASD, though challenges such as high dimensionality, noise, and small sample sizes hinder their clinical application. Methods: This study proposes a novel approach for ASD detection utilizing deep learning and advanced feature selection techniques. A hybrid model combining Stacked Sparse Denoising Autoencoder (SSDAE) and Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) is employed to extract relevant features from rs-fMRI data in the ABIDE I dataset, which was preprocessed using the CPAC pipeline. Feature selection is enhanced through an optimized Hiking Optimization Algorithm (HOA) that integrates DynamicOpposites Learning (DOL) and Double Attractors to improve convergence toward the optimal subset of features. Results: The proposed model is evaluated using multiple ASD datasets. The performance metrics include an average accuracy of 0.735, sensitivity of 0.765, and specificity of 0.752, surpassing the results of existing state-of-the-art methods. Discussion: The findings demonstrate the effectiveness of the hybrid deep learning approach for ASD detection. The enhanced feature selection process, coupled with the hybrid model, addresses limitations in current neuroimaging analyses and offers a promising direction for more accurate and clinically applicable ASD detection models. © © 2025 Nafisah, Mahmoud, Ewees, Khattap, Dahou, Alghamdi, Fares, Azmi Al-Betar and Abd Elaziz.},
	author_keywords = {autism detection; deep learning; double attractors; dynamic-opposite learning; feature selection; Hiking Optimization Algorithm; resting-state functional MRI (rs-fMRI)},
