	abstract = {Design research results must be effectively implemented in the industry to drive innovations. Various transfer routes exist for applying design support, requiring continuous engagement between industry and academia. Co-creation bridges the gap between research and application. This paper analyzes fourteen co-creation projects at the IPEK - Institute of Product Engineering at the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology (KIT). Universities, companies, and students had various needs and goals, addressed differently in the four format categories InnoX, InnoS, Live-Lab, and Training. These formats combined flexible and structured process elements according to ASD - Agile Systems Design. They enable stakeholders to leverage collective strength and creativity, expand knowledge and skills, and overcome challenges such as developing new product concepts and business models. They provide a basis for further research in co-creation innovation formats, fostering a closer link between research and practice. © 2025 Fraunhofer Verlag. All rights reserved.},
