	affiliations = {REVA University, School of Electronics and Communication Engineering, Bengaluru, KA, India},
	abstract = {Autism spectrum disorder (ASD) is a complex neurodevelopmental condition that manifests in various ways, impacting individuals’ social interactions, communication, and behavior. Early and accurate detection of autism is crucial for effective intervention and support. In recent years, medical image processing has emerged as a valuable tool in aiding the identification of ASD, particularly through the analysis of autism facial images. This study focuses on the application of image processing techniques to analyse facial images of individuals with autism. However, the presence of noise in autism facial images is a challenge to accurate analysis and diagnosis. Various types of noise, such as motion artifacts and imaging imperfections, can affect the quality of images produced from digital devices. Therefore, it becomes imperative to employ sophisticated image processing methods to denoise and enhance these images, facilitating a more precise examination of facial images associated with autism. This paper explores different noise removal techniques like median filter, a wiener filter, a gaussian filter and a guided filter are tailored for facial images, aiming to improve the accuracy of segmentation, feature extraction and classification models. The analysis includes the assessment of each filtering methods by applying salt, pepper, and speckle noise commonly encountered in autism facial images. The methods are analysed using performance metrics, including PSNR, SSIM, and MSE to evaluate the effectiveness of various filtering approaches. The experimental results indicate that the hybrid filter, which combines the median filter and Wiener filter, has exceptional efficacy in eliminating noise from autism facial images compared to other filtering techniques. The hybrid filter yielded a reduced MSE of 201.359, SSIM of 0.91409, and a raised PSNR of 25.0667. © The Author(s), under exclusive license to Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2024.},
	author_keywords = {Autism detection; gaussian filter; hybrid filter; median filter; salt and pepper noise; speckle noise; wiener filter},
	keywords = {Gaussian noise (electronic); Gluing; Image analysis; Image enhancement; Image segmentation; Medical image processing; Salt and pepper noise; Wiener filtering; Artifact removal; Autism detection; Autism spectrum disorders; Facial images; Gaussian filters; Hybrid filters; Median-Filter; Salt-and-pepper noise; Speckle noise; Wiener filter; Median filters},
