	abstract = {In this experiment, the study of children with Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) in the virtual space of the aquarium is conducted using eye-tracking technology. Firstly, two types of aquarium spaces re constructed using SketchUp, and Unity software is used to capture and collect eye-tracking data within the virtual space. Ten children with ASD (age M=9.20, SD=1.69) participated in a one-week experiment with a total duration of 2 hours. When collecting and processing data, the FixationCount, TotalFixationDuration, and Average FixationDuration of eye-tracking data are used as indicators. The results show that the eye-tracking fixation count (FC) score of children with ASD in virtual Space 1(M=12.00, SD=10.11) is lower than that in virtual Space 2(M=39.80, SD=29.43), the total fixation duration (TFD) score of children with ASD in virtual Space 1 (M=2221.40, SD=1837.27) is lower than that in virtual Space 2 (M=8877.00, SD=7692.96), and the average fixation duration (AFD) score of children with ASD in virtual Space 1(M=194.17, SD=46.12) is lower than that in virtual Space 2(M=204.34, SD=51.45). The eye-tracking indicators of FC and TFD in virtual space are both valid (P<0.05). In short, compared with virtual Space 1, virtual Space 2 can better attract the visual attention of children with ASD and is favored by the subjects, which means the subjects have more and longer fixations on virtual Space 2, which has certain positive significance for subsequent skill intervention in virtual space. © 2024 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {aquarium; children with ASD; eye-tracking technology; space design; Virtual Reality Technology},
