	year = {2024},
	pages = {13 - 20},
	doi = {10.1109/ICIMCIS63449.2024.10957079},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105004410185&doi=10.1109%2FICIMCIS63449.2024.10957079&partnerID=40&md5=553e55d7923688740016351c0c0262e1},
	affiliations = {Bina Nusantara University, Department of Computer Science, Jakarta, Indonesia},
	abstract = {As the global prevalence of Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) rises, effective interventions for cognitive impairments are increasingly needed. While Extended Reality (XR) technologies as intervention methods show promise, their real-world applications remain limited. This paper assesses the practical feasibility of XR as a means of ASD intervention through a Systematic Literature Review (SLR) of 22 experimental studies, focusing on the uncommonly discussed aspects of the approach-namely, the frequency and affordability of past used XR devices, the ASD demographic benefiting the most from the approach, as well as XR technology's potential long-term effects. Findings indicate that head-mounted displays (HMDs) are the most common devices, while affordability varies with intervention design. Non-wearable alternatives, like projectors and CAVEs, show promise as cost-effective options. XR interventions are most effective for high-functioning individuals with social, linguistic, and technological skills. Additionally, while there are indications of positive long-term outcomes in high-functioning intervention participants, conclusions are not yet definitive due to the lack of experimental studies spanning a longer term. © 2024 IEEE.},
