	affiliations = {Middle Tennessee State University, Computational and Data Science PhD Program, Murfreesboro, TN, United States; The University of Tennessee, Knoxville, Department of Mathematics, Knoxville, TN, United States; Middle Tennessee State University, Department of Computer Science, Murfreesboro, TN, United States},
	abstract = {This paper performs a classification task on data obtained from the Autism Brain Imaging Data Exchange (ABIDE) repository. In real-world case analysis, the number of autism spectrum disorder (ASD) patients is much smaller than typically developed people. To address this issue, this paper proposes the utilization of pairwise robust support vector machine (PRSVM) algorithms to classify autism spectrum disorder (ASD) patients. In this project's experiments, the correlation matrix derived from functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) data was employed as a classification feature. A comprehensive evaluation was conducted to compare the classification performance of PRSVM with various machine learning methods. The comparative analysis encompassed various aspects, including different data dimensions, imbalanced ratios, and sample sizes, providing valuable insights into the relative performance of the algorithms under different experimental conditions. The experimental results demonstrate that PRSVM can detect autistic patients more accurately when the data is imbalanced. Moreover, the results indicate that PRSVM outperforms or achieves comparable performance to other conventional classification methods in a variety of situations. Furthermore, our approach can be further improved by augmenting the training set with either exclusively normal person samples or by incorporating patient samples and normal people samples in a proportionate manner. This augmentation strategy holds promising application value, as it contributes to improving the performance and robustness of our method. © 2024 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {ASD classification; fMRI; imbalanced data; pairwise robust support vector machine},
	keywords = {Brain mapping; Support vector machines; Autism spectrum disorder classification; Autism spectrum disorders; Classification tasks; Functional magnetic resonance imaging; Imbalanced classification; Imbalanced data; Pairwise learning; Pairwise robust support vector machine; Performance; Support vectors machine; Diseases},
