	abstract = {This paper explores the potential for Wearable Color-Changing devices to facilitate emotion recognition and communication in children with autism spectrum disorder (ASD). Wearable technology that changes color in response to biometric data help children with ASD better understand their internal emotional states. The current study reviews existing wearable devices that visualize emotion through color changes based on heart rate, skin conductance, facial expressions, and other indicators of emotional arousal. It examines the feasibility of adapting this technology for children with ASD to provide real-time visual feedback on their emotional state. Quantitative data and qualitative feedback will be applied to assess the effectiveness of color-changing wearables in improving emotion recognition, self-regulation, and communication of emotions in children with ASD. Results inform the development of wearable assistive technologies that use color and visual cues to improve social and emotional skills among people with autism. Findings could ultimately improve the communication and understanding between children with ASD and their caregivers. © 2023 Copyright held by the owner/author(s). Publication rights licensed to ACM.},
