	abstract = {The agile software development (ASD) methods, differing from the traditional software development approach, prioritizes the autonomy of individuals and enables a timely response to market changes for customers. Initially designed for small, co-located, single-team projects, agile aims to facilitate efficient communication among team members and prompt decision-making (Boehm & Turner, 2005). The potential benefit of agile methods has prompted its adoption on a larger scale, involving multiple teams, which introduces challenges in inter-team coordination among diverse stakeholders. Coordination, as a critical aspect of agile methodology, has attracted scholarly attention in large-scale ASD. Although abundant case studies have explored the best practices of coordination, what is considered as “good” coordination” is still vague. In addition, there is a lack of measurement of inter-team coordination for large-scale projects. Although Hoegl et al. (2004) developed measurement coordination in multi-team projects, their context is within traditional project management. Moreover, although previous literature suggests that some of the agile principles cannot be fully operationalizable in large-scale projects (Rolland et al. 2016), there is a lack of systematic discussions problematizing the assumptions of large-scale ASD. Guided by coordination theory (Thompson, 2003), this study developed a conceptual framework for inter-team coordination in large-scale ASD. An exhaustive literature review was conducted on the best practices of coordination in large-scale agile projects, using the keywords "coordination," AND "agile," AND "large-scale.". The literature selected was published from 2017-2023 and must explicitly mention coordination practices. Using a grounded theorizing approach, we analyzed the literature and proposed four dimensions for inter-team coordination in large-scale ASD. We then conducted semi-structured interviews with practitioners with different roles t0 support, validate and supplement the dimensions and key practices of inter-team coordination. Then we develop and validate our measurement with practitioners. This study contributes a comprehensive definition and measurement for inter-team coordination in large-scale ASD, which established a solid foundation for future research. By mapping the key aspects and best practices on inter-team coordination to the agile manifesto, we also challenge the original agile assumptions in the context of large-scale agile projects and construct feasible assumptions to operationalize. For practitioners, understanding the key aspect of coordination is critical in managing a large-scale agile projects. As such, our framework can serve as a guide to evaluate their coordination mechanisms. © 2023 29th Annual Americas Conference on Information Systems, AMCIS 2023. All rights reserved.},
	keywords = {Agile manufacturing systems; Decision making; Human resource management; Information systems; Information use; Software design; Agile software development; Best practices; Inter-team coordinations; Key dimensions; Large-scale projects; Large-scales; Market changes; Software development approach; Software development methods; Team projects; Project management},
	correspondence_address = {Y. Ma; Florida International University, United States; email: yma021@fiu.edu},
	publisher = {Association for Information Systems},
	isbn = {9781713893592},
	language = {English},
	abbrev_source_title = {Annu. Am. Conf. Inf. Syst., AMCIS},
	type = {Conference paper},
